1
00:00:29,362 --> 00:00:32,297
Woman:
Mostly the job is to ask questions.

2
00:00:32,332 --> 00:00:34,391
The frustrating part,

3
00:00:34,434 --> 00:00:36,902
the part that drives you crazy,

4
00:00:36,936 --> 00:00:40,269
is that the people you really
want to talk to

5
00:00:40,306 --> 00:00:42,035
are dead.

6
00:01:19,245 --> 00:01:22,908
Help me!
Please help me!

7
00:01:22,949 --> 00:01:25,179
Please!
Please!

8
00:01:25,218 --> 00:01:27,118
No, leave me alone.
Please!

9
00:01:27,153 --> 00:01:29,849
Help me!
Help me please!

10
00:01:29,889 --> 00:01:32,255
Help!
Someone help me!

11
00:01:32,292 --> 00:01:34,351
Please!

12
00:01:34,394 --> 00:01:36,988
Please, someone help me.

13
00:01:37,030 --> 00:01:39,123
Please.
Please.

14
00:02:23,143 --> 00:02:25,338
Hey.

15
00:02:25,378 --> 00:02:27,573
Lieutenant.

16
00:02:28,648 --> 00:02:30,548
Any idea who she is?

17
00:02:30,583 --> 00:02:32,813
No.

18
00:02:32,852 --> 00:02:34,945
I didn't want to move her.

19
00:02:43,363 --> 00:02:45,524
God, it's awful.

20
00:02:47,700 --> 00:02:50,168
There are grass stains on her pants.

21
00:02:50,203 --> 00:02:52,171
He dragged her.

22
00:02:55,575 --> 00:02:57,236
You okay?

23
00:02:57,277 --> 00:02:59,040
Did you just touch me?

24
00:02:59,078 --> 00:03:01,069
Huh-uh.

25
00:03:02,949 --> 00:03:04,814
Wow.

26
00:03:04,851 --> 00:03:07,445
I've had way too much coffee.

27
00:03:08,988 --> 00:03:10,888
Um...

28
00:03:10,924 --> 00:03:14,155
looks like there's some kind of
white hair on her jacket.

29
00:03:14,194 --> 00:03:16,992
- Maybe animal fur?
- Man: Yeah, I saw that.

30
00:03:24,204 --> 00:03:26,672
- Watch your step.
- I know.

31
00:03:46,125 --> 00:03:47,956
Think it's hers?

32
00:03:47,994 --> 00:03:50,155
Yeah.

33
00:03:50,196 --> 00:03:52,130
How do you know?

34
00:03:52,165 --> 00:03:55,430
He raped her and then
strangled her to death.

35
00:03:57,036 --> 00:03:59,163
Then put her pants back on?

36
00:03:59,205 --> 00:04:01,298
That's my guess.

37
00:04:15,221 --> 00:04:16,745
There you are.

38
00:04:17,857 --> 00:04:19,916
Here.

39
00:04:19,959 --> 00:04:22,257
- Brought you some tea.
- Thanks.

40
00:04:22,295 --> 00:04:24,229
You're welcome.

41
00:04:30,169 --> 00:04:32,569
You making a war room?

42
00:04:34,140 --> 00:04:37,735
Carla had asthma.
I think the cat hair was in the car.

43
00:04:37,777 --> 00:04:40,075
Uh-huh.

44
00:04:45,418 --> 00:04:47,716
So...

45
00:04:49,122 --> 00:04:51,147
you're not gonna, um...

46
00:04:51,190 --> 00:04:53,886
stay up all night with this stuff,
are you?

47
00:04:53,926 --> 00:04:55,553
No.

48
00:04:55,595 --> 00:04:57,790
It's couple's night.
I'm sleeping with you.

49
00:04:57,830 --> 00:04:59,798
Uh-huh.

50
00:04:59,832 --> 00:05:01,732
When?

51
00:05:01,768 --> 00:05:03,599
Soon.

52
00:05:03,636 --> 00:05:05,194
Good.

53
00:05:35,168 --> 00:05:37,728
- Don't be mad.
- I'm not.

54
00:05:41,207 --> 00:05:42,970
Can I ask you one question?

55
00:05:45,144 --> 00:05:47,009
What?

56
00:05:48,147 --> 00:05:50,445
Why do you think she got in the car?

57
00:05:56,656 --> 00:05:58,248
It's kind of late, honey.

58
00:05:58,291 --> 00:06:00,486
Why don't you give it a rest, huh?

59
00:06:11,671 --> 00:06:13,605
Why did you get in the car?

60
00:06:23,316 --> 00:06:26,444
Man: The FBI seems to agree
with the initial profiles.

61
00:06:26,486 --> 00:06:28,920
They feel there's a good chance
the killer's out of state;

62
00:06:28,955 --> 00:06:31,389
sloppy, low intelligence;

63
00:06:31,424 --> 00:06:34,916
someone with a knowledge
of Rochester who resides elsewhere;

64
00:06:34,961 --> 00:06:37,555
probably a marginal type personality.

65
00:06:41,000 --> 00:06:42,934
Okay, Megan.

66
00:06:42,969 --> 00:06:46,029
He's not sloppy.
He didn't choose her at random.

67
00:06:46,072 --> 00:06:49,439
And we're wasting our time looking
for truck drivers and transients.

68
00:06:49,475 --> 00:06:51,238
The guy chased her in reverse
in broad daylight

69
00:06:51,277 --> 00:06:53,268
in front of a dozen witnesses,
for Christ's sakes.

70
00:06:53,312 --> 00:06:55,507
The kid got lucky for 20 seconds.

71
00:06:55,548 --> 00:06:58,312
He's cold and calculating
and he's gonna do it again.

72
00:06:58,351 --> 00:07:00,012
No, we don't have a serial killer.

73
00:07:00,052 --> 00:07:02,987
He's an emotional impulse-driven
bumbling fuck up.

74
00:07:03,022 --> 00:07:05,855
He's probably 1000 miles
from here running in terror.

75
00:07:07,393 --> 00:07:09,452
What do you think, Ken?

76
00:07:14,367 --> 00:07:16,892
Carla Castillo was a smart kid.

77
00:07:18,037 --> 00:07:20,403
I don't think she's get
into a car with anyone

78
00:07:20,440 --> 00:07:24,376
who looked like even
a marginal transient.

79
00:07:24,410 --> 00:07:27,106
I'm not saying the guy looks
like fucking Leatherface.

80
00:07:27,146 --> 00:07:28,545
I'm saying...

81
00:07:28,581 --> 00:07:30,879
The crime scene had all the earmarks
of a disorganized killer.

82
00:07:30,917 --> 00:07:33,317
Do you know how many people have
the same first and last initial?

83
00:07:33,352 --> 00:07:35,320
2%.

84
00:07:35,354 --> 00:07:39,120
So the killer found a way to get
Carla Castillo into his car

85
00:07:39,158 --> 00:07:41,456
and he drove her to Churchville.
That is not random.

86
00:07:41,494 --> 00:07:44,019
- It might be.
- It's got nothing to do with the initials.

87
00:07:44,063 --> 00:07:45,928
He watched her for a long time.

88
00:07:45,965 --> 00:07:49,128
He waited and he did it exactly
the way he wanted to.

89
00:07:49,168 --> 00:07:52,160
Any loss of control he displays
is intentional.

90
00:07:52,205 --> 00:07:54,503
Megan, we've interviewed everybody
who ever met this girl

91
00:07:54,540 --> 00:07:56,269
and we've got nothing.

92
00:07:56,309 --> 00:07:58,777
Well, please let me interview them again.

93
00:08:51,998 --> 00:08:53,966
Mr. Castillo?

94
00:08:54,000 --> 00:08:56,332
Hey.
You have news?

95
00:08:56,369 --> 00:08:58,303
No.
Nothing concrete yet.

96
00:08:58,337 --> 00:09:01,363
No.
You're here to see me then?

97
00:09:01,407 --> 00:09:04,968
Yeah. I was hoping maybe
we could talk a little more.

98
00:09:05,011 --> 00:09:06,945
Can I get you something?

99
00:09:06,979 --> 00:09:08,606
Hank, this lady is a police officer.

100
00:09:08,648 --> 00:09:10,616
Oh.
Soda? Something?

101
00:09:10,650 --> 00:09:11,878
No, thank you.

102
00:09:11,918 --> 00:09:13,783
How about some coffee?
Just made it fresh.

103
00:09:13,819 --> 00:09:16,379
That would be great.
Thanks.

104
00:09:16,422 --> 00:09:18,720
- Let's go upstairs.
- Okay.

105
00:09:20,459 --> 00:09:23,087
Megan:
Was Tuesday the only day you saw Carla?

106
00:09:23,129 --> 00:09:26,292
Pretty much, usually.
Her mother and I had a falling out.

107
00:09:26,332 --> 00:09:29,768
I would like to have seen
her more, don't get me wrong.

108
00:09:29,802 --> 00:09:32,362
And what would you do?

109
00:09:32,405 --> 00:09:35,101
Have dinner.

110
00:09:35,141 --> 00:09:37,200
Watch TV.
Talk.

111
00:09:37,243 --> 00:09:39,370
What did she like to eat?

112
00:09:40,613 --> 00:09:43,446
You think I had something to do
with what happened, huh?

113
00:09:43,482 --> 00:09:45,746
No.

114
00:09:45,785 --> 00:09:48,413
Then why are you asking me
this stuff again?

115
00:09:48,454 --> 00:09:51,912
I want to find the man that hurt
your daughter, Jay.

116
00:09:51,958 --> 00:09:54,791
I need to understand everything
that was happening

117
00:09:54,827 --> 00:09:56,556
because anything could be important.

118
00:09:58,764 --> 00:10:01,198
Spaghetti, French fries,

119
00:10:01,233 --> 00:10:03,428
Chinese takeout,

120
00:10:03,469 --> 00:10:05,994
tacos from the deli.

121
00:10:06,038 --> 00:10:07,699
Great.

122
00:10:07,740 --> 00:10:11,506
In some of the photos she's wearing
a medallion of some kind.

123
00:10:11,544 --> 00:10:14,035
Jay:
St. Philomena.

124
00:10:14,080 --> 00:10:17,208
The patron saint of children.

125
00:10:17,249 --> 00:10:18,682
Her grandmother gave her that.

126
00:10:18,718 --> 00:10:20,686
I haven't found it.

127
00:10:20,720 --> 00:10:23,655
She wasn't wearing it and it wasn't
recovered at the scene.

128
00:10:31,897 --> 00:10:34,058
Maybe she lost it.

129
00:10:35,968 --> 00:10:38,937
What did she talk about
when she came over?

130
00:10:40,206 --> 00:10:43,573
Schoolwork, friends...

131
00:10:44,610 --> 00:10:47,773
kid stuff, like I told you.

132
00:10:53,986 --> 00:10:55,977
You okay?

133
00:10:58,224 --> 00:11:00,590
Yes.

134
00:11:00,626 --> 00:11:02,594
Um, sorry.

135
00:11:02,628 --> 00:11:04,391
What were her friends' names?

136
00:11:23,082 --> 00:11:25,482
Carla saw her father on Tuesdays?

137
00:11:25,518 --> 00:11:27,543
Yes.

138
00:11:27,586 --> 00:11:30,111
Until 6:00
or 7:00 at night?

139
00:11:30,156 --> 00:11:32,716
That's right.

140
00:11:32,758 --> 00:11:36,421
I spoke to the bus drivers
who run that route on Tuesdays.

141
00:11:36,462 --> 00:11:38,589
They weren't very helpful.

142
00:11:38,631 --> 00:11:41,498
They couldn't remember
whether or not they saw her.

143
00:11:42,835 --> 00:11:45,303
Carla was a quiet girl.

144
00:11:45,337 --> 00:11:48,773
You would not even notice
when she was in the room.

145
00:11:50,876 --> 00:11:53,709
Was there anyone else
she regularly visited?

146
00:11:53,746 --> 00:11:55,304
Other family?

147
00:11:55,347 --> 00:11:57,474
No.

148
00:11:57,516 --> 00:11:59,711
Jay's mom.

149
00:12:01,187 --> 00:12:04,418
She was the only family
in Rochester.

150
00:12:04,457 --> 00:12:07,017
She died about a month ago.

151
00:12:08,194 --> 00:12:10,822
We didn't get along well
when she was alive.

152
00:12:12,531 --> 00:12:15,022
We hadn't seen her in years.

153
00:12:15,067 --> 00:12:18,434
Did Carla have any older friends
that you might have forgotten?

154
00:12:18,471 --> 00:12:20,405
You asked me all this before.

155
00:12:20,439 --> 00:12:24,034
I really want to help you
but I don't know how.

156
00:12:25,911 --> 00:12:28,106
I'm so sorry, I...

157
00:12:30,015 --> 00:12:32,677
I just don't feel good.

158
00:12:32,718 --> 00:12:35,118
Okay.

159
00:12:35,154 --> 00:12:38,021
Do you mind if I look
in her room again?

160
00:13:54,633 --> 00:13:57,431
Carla, what are you hiding?

161
00:14:31,136 --> 00:14:33,263
Carla's voice:
Megan.

162
00:14:34,273 --> 00:14:36,366
Megan.

163
00:14:38,077 --> 00:14:40,272
Hey.

164
00:14:41,780 --> 00:14:43,839
I'm... I'm sorry.
L...

165
00:14:44,984 --> 00:14:47,646
I was looking under the bed
and I was startled.

166
00:14:47,686 --> 00:14:49,483
You should go.

167
00:14:54,426 --> 00:14:56,291
I apologize.

168
00:15:15,915 --> 00:15:17,542
Uh-huh.

169
00:15:33,732 --> 00:15:35,859
Where are you?

170
00:16:03,062 --> 00:16:06,862
Um, it's time for you to stop
working on Castillo.

171
00:16:10,269 --> 00:16:12,066
It's...

172
00:16:14,073 --> 00:16:16,405
It's just that it's having
a bad effect on you.

173
00:16:16,442 --> 00:16:18,842
People are complaining
about your behavior.

174
00:16:18,877 --> 00:16:20,276
What people?

175
00:16:22,548 --> 00:16:27,508
Look, Ray, you know
I get a little bit obsessed.

176
00:16:27,553 --> 00:16:29,384
That's my process.

177
00:16:29,421 --> 00:16:31,981
And yes, I know that can be
spooky to some people.

178
00:16:32,024 --> 00:16:34,686
Everyone has given credible deference
to your process, Megan.

179
00:16:34,727 --> 00:16:37,389
And because of your track record...

180
00:16:38,931 --> 00:16:41,365
it may be too much though.

181
00:16:41,400 --> 00:16:43,960
People say they've seen you

182
00:16:44,003 --> 00:16:46,233
talking to yourself.

183
00:16:47,706 --> 00:16:49,367
That's bullshit.

184
00:16:49,408 --> 00:16:51,501
Yeah.

185
00:16:51,543 --> 00:16:53,704
This is the number of my psychologist.

186
00:16:55,748 --> 00:16:57,943
She's been incredibly
helpful to me.

187
00:16:57,983 --> 00:17:00,213
- It's bullshit, Captain.
- No no, shh.

188
00:17:00,252 --> 00:17:02,914
She's expecting your call.

189
00:17:02,955 --> 00:17:05,753
So what I want you to do is take
the vacation time you saved up

190
00:17:05,791 --> 00:17:08,419
and just, you know, cool out
and get a handle on things.

191
00:17:12,765 --> 00:17:14,255
I'm not going to stop.

192
00:17:18,337 --> 00:17:20,237
You most certainly are.

193
00:17:49,802 --> 00:17:53,431
Carla's voice:
Megan, help me.

194
00:17:54,907 --> 00:17:57,876
Help me, Megan.

195
00:17:57,910 --> 00:18:01,903
Help me.
Why don't you help me?

196
00:18:01,947 --> 00:18:05,075
Help me.
Help me.

197
00:18:05,117 --> 00:18:07,779
Help me.
Help me, Megan.

198
00:18:07,820 --> 00:18:09,913
- Tell me.
- Yes.

199
00:18:09,955 --> 00:18:11,946
Carla's voice: I'm dead.
'Cause I'm dead.

200
00:18:11,990 --> 00:18:14,788
'Cause I'm dead.

201
00:18:17,963 --> 00:18:20,124
I'm so sorry, Carla.

202
00:18:22,301 --> 00:18:24,963
I can't find him.

203
00:18:36,348 --> 00:18:38,782
Please.

204
00:18:38,817 --> 00:18:42,184
I don't even sleep anymore.

205
00:18:45,290 --> 00:18:48,817
Carla's voice:
Help me! Help me!

206
00:18:48,861 --> 00:18:51,796
Help me!

207
00:19:00,572 --> 00:19:02,199
Help me!

208
00:19:33,005 --> 00:19:34,870
Honey?

209
00:19:44,716 --> 00:19:48,152
Jesus. Megan!

210
00:19:48,187 --> 00:19:49,848
Megan!

211
00:20:12,945 --> 00:20:14,776
Thank you.

212
00:20:18,750 --> 00:20:20,775
Hi.

213
00:20:20,819 --> 00:20:23,583
- How's she doing?
- Stable.

214
00:20:25,123 --> 00:20:27,284
What happened?

215
00:20:27,326 --> 00:20:30,352
I believe she's had
what is referred to

216
00:20:30,395 --> 00:20:33,455
as an adult onset of schizophrenia.

217
00:20:33,498 --> 00:20:35,659
Schizophrenia?

218
00:20:35,701 --> 00:20:37,931
How is that possible?

219
00:20:37,970 --> 00:20:40,268
She's been normal
her whole life.

220
00:20:41,373 --> 00:20:43,933
Has she had some sort
of trauma recently?

221
00:20:45,777 --> 00:20:47,745
I mean, she was...

222
00:20:47,779 --> 00:20:50,407
I don't know if it was traumatic or not,

223
00:20:50,449 --> 00:20:54,647
but she was recently taken off
the Carla Castillo investigation.

224
00:20:56,888 --> 00:20:58,651
What now?

225
00:20:58,690 --> 00:21:01,659
I mean, will she get better?

226
00:21:03,695 --> 00:21:05,788
We've got a long road ahead.

227
00:21:22,281 --> 00:21:24,511
Carla's voice:
Help me.

228
00:21:24,616 --> 00:21:27,881
Tim: It's like my brain would be
trapped in a loop.

229
00:21:27,919 --> 00:21:31,082
There's no way to stop it.

230
00:21:31,123 --> 00:21:34,581
Just the same upsetting,
awful thoughts over and over.

231
00:21:34,626 --> 00:21:38,027
<i>I would just be racked with panic 24l7.</i>

232
00:21:39,364 --> 00:21:41,924
My family has trouble understanding

233
00:21:41,967 --> 00:21:44,527
why I did the things I did.

234
00:21:47,406 --> 00:21:49,306
I guess I can't blame them.

235
00:21:49,341 --> 00:21:51,809
But I wish they would talk to me.

236
00:21:53,745 --> 00:21:56,009
Anyway, my doctor's
changing medication

237
00:21:56,048 --> 00:21:57,675
and they seem to be helping again.

238
00:21:59,851 --> 00:22:01,842
Lawyer says the charges
might be dropped,

239
00:22:01,887 --> 00:22:04,219
so I guess things are looking up.

240
00:22:06,925 --> 00:22:09,393
Richard:
Thank you for sharing that with us.

241
00:22:09,428 --> 00:22:12,454
I can relate completely
to your wanting your family

242
00:22:12,497 --> 00:22:14,431
to talk with you.

243
00:22:14,466 --> 00:22:16,832
I put myself in this chair

244
00:22:16,868 --> 00:22:20,395
by crashing my brother's Lexus
into a wall.

245
00:22:20,439 --> 00:22:22,669
It didn't work.
He still didn't speak to me.

246
00:22:24,409 --> 00:22:26,502
And now he's gone.

247
00:22:26,545 --> 00:22:28,945
But, uh...

248
00:22:28,980 --> 00:22:31,312
does anybody else wanna...?

249
00:22:33,251 --> 00:22:36,914
Well, a lot of what Tim
was saying sounded familiar.

250
00:22:38,156 --> 00:22:40,750
I lost my fiancée to my disease.

251
00:22:40,792 --> 00:22:42,726
I lost my career.

252
00:22:42,761 --> 00:22:44,786
I was well respected

253
00:22:44,830 --> 00:22:47,298
but now I realize

254
00:22:47,332 --> 00:22:49,630
that a good deal of my success

255
00:22:49,668 --> 00:22:53,195
came from the way I would fixate

256
00:22:53,238 --> 00:22:56,036
when I was on a case.

257
00:22:56,074 --> 00:22:59,635
I guess I would go a bit manic,

258
00:22:59,678 --> 00:23:03,114
which would sometimes
allow me an insight.

259
00:23:05,751 --> 00:23:09,243
I guess I was able
to keep it under control,

260
00:23:09,287 --> 00:23:12,222
to sort of channel it
for a while.

261
00:23:12,257 --> 00:23:14,782
But two years ago

262
00:23:14,826 --> 00:23:18,125
I had a case that...
I don't know,

263
00:23:18,163 --> 00:23:20,631
blew my circuits.

264
00:23:21,933 --> 00:23:25,460
My failure to solve it
left me desolate.

265
00:23:25,504 --> 00:23:28,337
I couldn't get it
out of my mind.

266
00:23:28,373 --> 00:23:30,603
I was hallucinating around it

267
00:23:30,642 --> 00:23:34,806
and I couldn't imagine a time

268
00:23:34,846 --> 00:23:38,475
when it wasn't with me
constantly.

269
00:23:38,517 --> 00:23:41,953
So I tried to kill myself.

270
00:23:44,022 --> 00:23:46,081
But now the doctors say

271
00:23:46,124 --> 00:23:48,422
that by doing all the right things,

272
00:23:48,460 --> 00:23:51,327
ignoring my ghosts,

273
00:23:51,363 --> 00:23:54,059
trusting my safe people...

274
00:23:54,099 --> 00:23:58,126
Parks and, well, you...

275
00:23:58,170 --> 00:24:01,606
that I have a pretty good chance at

276
00:24:01,640 --> 00:24:04,734
leading a more or less
functional life.

277
00:24:06,611 --> 00:24:08,272
Richard:
So you're back at work?

278
00:24:08,313 --> 00:24:10,213
Rubber gun division.

279
00:24:10,248 --> 00:24:13,115
They have to give me a job
or the union will go after the city.

280
00:24:13,151 --> 00:24:14,482
Oh.

281
00:24:14,519 --> 00:24:16,680
So they have me in
the records department

282
00:24:16,721 --> 00:24:19,246
where I won't get
in any trouble.

283
00:24:19,291 --> 00:24:21,225
It's better than it sounds.

284
00:24:21,259 --> 00:24:24,956
Does your ex...
he still works there?

285
00:24:24,996 --> 00:24:26,293
- Oh yeah.
- Yeah?

286
00:24:26,331 --> 00:24:29,357
He's made captain.
So he's the boss.

287
00:24:29,401 --> 00:24:31,699
I have him to thank for the job.

288
00:24:31,736 --> 00:24:33,704
But if it weren't for you,

289
00:24:33,738 --> 00:24:35,467
I never would have made
it out of Park Ridge.

290
00:24:35,507 --> 00:24:38,442
No no. Now that's the first
dumb thing I've heard you say.

291
00:24:38,477 --> 00:24:40,945
Well, then you haven't been listening.

292
00:24:40,979 --> 00:24:43,072
What about you?

293
00:24:43,114 --> 00:24:45,878
- Are you heading back to work?
- No no.

294
00:24:45,917 --> 00:24:48,317
My doctor said I have to stay
away from calculators.

295
00:24:48,353 --> 00:24:50,981
I know what you must have
gone through.

296
00:24:51,022 --> 00:24:53,684
Numbers are a bitch.

297
00:24:53,725 --> 00:24:56,751
I used to calculate the probability
of different scenarios

298
00:24:56,795 --> 00:24:58,524
over and over.

299
00:24:58,563 --> 00:25:01,589
Like the chance that
the three C's were random.

300
00:25:01,633 --> 00:25:04,227
Your Castillo murder case?

301
00:25:04,269 --> 00:25:07,432
Yeah.
If 2% of the population

302
00:25:07,472 --> 00:25:10,236
have matching first and last initials

303
00:25:10,275 --> 00:25:13,540
what are the chances
that Carla Castillo

304
00:25:13,578 --> 00:25:16,911
would be dumped in a town
that started with the letter C?

305
00:25:16,948 --> 00:25:19,246
I'd plug in different variables

306
00:25:19,284 --> 00:25:22,344
but I never got a number
that was lower than one in 1400.

307
00:25:26,825 --> 00:25:28,690
You may never know.

308
00:25:30,228 --> 00:25:32,219
And you may have to live with that.

309
00:25:37,502 --> 00:25:39,697
You're a smart crazy, Ledge.

310
00:26:47,138 --> 00:26:48,901
Where is it?

311
00:27:08,326 --> 00:27:11,227
Jean, it's the little girl.

312
00:27:11,262 --> 00:27:13,856
It's the Walsh girl.

313
00:27:13,898 --> 00:27:16,526
Megan:
He has six outstanding tickets.

314
00:27:16,568 --> 00:27:18,934
Yes, you can impound his car.

315
00:27:18,970 --> 00:27:20,870
No problem.

316
00:27:31,316 --> 00:27:34,080
- Hey, guys, what's up?
- Nothing.

317
00:27:43,361 --> 00:27:45,522
Angelo, get down there.
See if you can get me a witness.

318
00:27:45,563 --> 00:27:47,531
Go now.
Go ahead.

319
00:27:49,467 --> 00:27:51,162
How did the press
find out about that?

320
00:27:51,202 --> 00:27:53,193
- Ken.
- Not now.

321
00:27:53,238 --> 00:27:55,138
No, go ahead, Bob.
Continue.

322
00:27:55,173 --> 00:27:57,004
What?

323
00:28:26,571 --> 00:28:30,598
Wendy Walsh, driven 30 miles
to be killed in Webster.

324
00:28:33,144 --> 00:28:34,577
Why are you looking at me like that?

325
00:28:34,612 --> 00:28:36,375
I'm not gonna freak out.

326
00:28:36,414 --> 00:28:38,746
Okay, so you were right.

327
00:28:38,783 --> 00:28:40,944
But that doesn't alter
the fact that you...

328
00:28:40,985 --> 00:28:42,782
Had a meltdown?
I know.

329
00:28:42,821 --> 00:28:44,288
How did he strangle her?

330
00:28:46,057 --> 00:28:48,992
Oh, come on, Ken.
How did he do it?

331
00:28:50,695 --> 00:28:52,629
There hasn't been a autopsy yet.

332
00:28:52,664 --> 00:28:56,259
From the marks on her neck
it doesn't look like he used his hands.

333
00:29:00,371 --> 00:29:02,168
He used a belt

334
00:29:02,207 --> 00:29:05,005
from behind, okay?

335
00:29:06,211 --> 00:29:08,406
Look, Meg,

336
00:29:08,446 --> 00:29:10,038
this is pointless.

337
00:29:10,081 --> 00:29:12,242
You're not an investigator anymore.

338
00:29:27,298 --> 00:29:29,630
I can help.
You know it.

339
00:29:29,667 --> 00:29:33,103
Look, Meg,

340
00:29:33,138 --> 00:29:35,698
I don't think you should
take on the stress, okay?

341
00:29:35,740 --> 00:29:37,332
Ken, I'm fine.

342
00:29:37,375 --> 00:29:39,707
Look, I'm taking medication.

343
00:29:39,744 --> 00:29:41,006
I know the warning signs.

344
00:29:41,045 --> 00:29:43,104
I'm in a support group.
I'm in therapy.

345
00:29:43,148 --> 00:29:44,809
I'm not gonna snap

346
00:29:44,849 --> 00:29:46,646
and I need to do this.

347
00:29:46,684 --> 00:29:48,447
- You want more coffee?
- No, thank you.

348
00:29:48,486 --> 00:29:50,454
Yes, fill his cup.

349
00:29:50,488 --> 00:29:52,615
He can't go home yet.

350
00:29:55,360 --> 00:29:58,488
There was cat hair,
wasn't there?

351
00:30:01,232 --> 00:30:03,826
I knew it.
I knew it last time.

352
00:30:03,868 --> 00:30:06,496
Let me help you, please, Ken.

353
00:30:11,442 --> 00:30:13,603
You can ride with Harper

354
00:30:13,645 --> 00:30:16,375
on a trial basis, okay?

355
00:30:16,414 --> 00:30:18,348
You're a consultant only.

356
00:30:18,383 --> 00:30:21,443
You observe, advise
and consult, that's it.

357
00:30:21,486 --> 00:30:23,784
You don't conduct interviews
on your own.

358
00:30:23,822 --> 00:30:25,449
He takes the lead.

359
00:30:25,490 --> 00:30:27,890
You don't handle evidence,
you don't go near evidence.

360
00:30:27,926 --> 00:30:31,487
If we catch this guy I don't want
some defense attorney

361
00:30:31,529 --> 00:30:35,659
using your mental history
to destroy our case.

362
00:30:39,304 --> 00:30:42,137
Jesus, this is a bad idea.

363
00:30:44,342 --> 00:30:46,776
And you don't load your weapon,
all right?

364
00:30:46,811 --> 00:30:50,076
Ken, this is a good idea.

365
00:30:50,114 --> 00:30:52,014
You want to catch him too.

366
00:30:52,050 --> 00:30:53,881
Can I finish eating now, please?

367
00:30:53,918 --> 00:30:55,146
Yes.

368
00:30:55,186 --> 00:30:57,154
Thank you.

369
00:30:57,188 --> 00:30:59,156
You meeting Eileen?

370
00:31:00,325 --> 00:31:02,885
How'd you know?

371
00:31:02,927 --> 00:31:05,259
Everyone knows.

372
00:31:05,296 --> 00:31:08,356
She's very pretty.

373
00:31:10,501 --> 00:31:12,298
Thanks.

374
00:31:29,454 --> 00:31:31,046
Ken:
Everyone in this room,

375
00:31:31,089 --> 00:31:33,023
you are now assigned
to the task force

376
00:31:33,057 --> 00:31:35,491
for the Castillo-Walsh
investigations full time.

377
00:31:35,526 --> 00:31:39,121
I want you to clear your desks
of everything else you're working on.

378
00:31:39,163 --> 00:31:42,257
Now we're proceeding
with the assumption

379
00:31:42,300 --> 00:31:44,894
the killings were perpetrated
by the same individual...

380
00:31:46,237 --> 00:31:50,333
and that we're dealing with
an active local serial killer.

381
00:31:50,375 --> 00:31:52,570
Both victims have traces

382
00:31:52,610 --> 00:31:55,044
of the same white cat hair
on their clothing.

383
00:31:55,079 --> 00:31:57,479
Now in the matter of the Walsh killing,

384
00:31:57,515 --> 00:32:00,109
we have jurisdiction
over the kidnapping only.

385
00:32:00,151 --> 00:32:02,449
Since the murder took place
in Webster,

386
00:32:02,487 --> 00:32:05,217
we're gonna be sharing the case
with Webster PD

387
00:32:05,256 --> 00:32:07,156
who have promised
to cooperate fully.

388
00:32:08,359 --> 00:32:10,589
Ken:
Biggs, you'll be coordinating with them.

389
00:32:10,628 --> 00:32:14,120
Now I want all known pedophiles
in the area questioned.

390
00:32:14,165 --> 00:32:16,963
I want surveillance on the dump sites,

391
00:32:17,001 --> 00:32:18,832
the victim's graves

392
00:32:18,870 --> 00:32:21,532
and the general neighborhoods
from where the girls disappeared.

393
00:32:23,441 --> 00:32:25,306
Now I'm sure I don't have
to remind you all

394
00:32:25,343 --> 00:32:28,801
to conduct yourselves calmly
and professionally.

395
00:32:32,216 --> 00:32:34,946
Okay, that's it.
Harper, I need a word with you.

396
00:32:55,440 --> 00:32:58,307
I charted everywhere
Carla commonly went.

397
00:32:58,343 --> 00:33:00,937
Blue means by bus,
red means on foot.

398
00:33:00,979 --> 00:33:03,709
There's got to be some crossover
with Wendy somewhere.

399
00:33:11,022 --> 00:33:13,456
- What?
- Nothing.

400
00:33:14,826 --> 00:33:16,726
What's on your mind, Harper?

401
00:33:16,761 --> 00:33:18,592
Honesty breeds trust.

402
00:33:18,629 --> 00:33:20,961
No it doesn't.

403
00:33:22,233 --> 00:33:25,259
All right, come on.
Just say it.

404
00:33:25,303 --> 00:33:27,567
What, you think I'm going
to endanger you?

405
00:33:27,605 --> 00:33:30,403
I think you're gonna endanger this case

406
00:33:30,441 --> 00:33:32,773
and possibly yourself.

407
00:33:32,810 --> 00:33:35,404
I think you were an excellent detective

408
00:33:35,446 --> 00:33:38,108
who should've accepted full disability
for your mental illness.

409
00:33:38,149 --> 00:33:41,641
I know that the department
keeps you around out of pity.

410
00:33:41,686 --> 00:33:44,712
And I think the captain's
decision is insane

411
00:33:44,756 --> 00:33:47,691
and it wouldn't happen if it weren't
for your past relationship.

412
00:33:47,725 --> 00:33:49,556
You trust me now?

413
00:33:53,564 --> 00:33:55,464
I can help with this.

414
00:33:55,500 --> 00:33:58,435
Honey, Captain tells me you're gonna
consult, you're gonna consult.

415
00:33:58,469 --> 00:34:00,164
What the hell can I do about it?

416
00:34:00,204 --> 00:34:02,729
Just keep in the back
and stay out of the way.

417
00:34:06,344 --> 00:34:08,107
You think it's okay
to call me honey?

418
00:34:10,114 --> 00:34:13,174
No, that was inappropriate.

419
00:34:15,820 --> 00:34:17,754
Apology accepted.

420
00:34:20,158 --> 00:34:22,956
Harper: Was there anyone who took
an unusual interest in Wendy?

421
00:34:27,331 --> 00:34:28,696
Unusual, no.

422
00:34:30,068 --> 00:34:32,434
She was a great kid.

423
00:34:32,470 --> 00:34:34,370
Everyone liked her.

424
00:34:34,405 --> 00:34:38,205
She was baptized.
Are you active in the church?

425
00:34:38,242 --> 00:34:40,767
We go...

426
00:34:40,812 --> 00:34:44,145
we went to...

427
00:34:44,182 --> 00:34:48,141
Mass on Sundays
at St. Michael's

428
00:34:48,186 --> 00:34:51,553
and Wendy went to a church-sponsored
camping trip last summer.

429
00:34:53,024 --> 00:34:55,356
She met her friend Zoe there.

430
00:34:57,495 --> 00:34:59,759
They used to...

431
00:35:12,276 --> 00:35:15,074
She and Zoe were best friends.

432
00:35:16,848 --> 00:35:20,147
I'd like to make a list
of all of Wendy's friends.

433
00:35:20,184 --> 00:35:23,381
Oh, they're right in her cell phone.

434
00:35:25,289 --> 00:35:27,223
Jim, would you...?

435
00:35:29,627 --> 00:35:31,652
Jim?

436
00:35:40,972 --> 00:35:44,430
She'd always forget this.

437
00:35:44,475 --> 00:35:46,636
And then she wouldn't be able to

438
00:35:46,677 --> 00:35:49,874
call me when she...

439
00:35:51,616 --> 00:35:53,311
when she needed me.

440
00:35:54,952 --> 00:35:57,921
- Jim.
- When she needed me.

441
00:36:00,057 --> 00:36:02,218
Jim, let them help us, hmm?

442
00:36:04,495 --> 00:36:06,326
Let them help us.

443
00:36:06,364 --> 00:36:08,594
It's all right.

444
00:36:13,638 --> 00:36:15,936
It's all right.

445
00:36:15,973 --> 00:36:18,441
- Here you go.
- Thank you.

446
00:36:18,476 --> 00:36:20,967
Would you mind if I looked
in Wendy's room?

447
00:36:21,012 --> 00:36:23,879
No.
Right up the stairs.

448
00:37:56,173 --> 00:37:58,664
- Girl's voice: Megan.
- Hey, I just got a call.

449
00:37:58,709 --> 00:38:00,836
A homeless man
saw the abduction.

450
00:38:03,047 --> 00:38:05,447
Man:
I think I saw her, you know?

451
00:38:05,483 --> 00:38:07,417
I'm a witness, you know?

452
00:38:07,451 --> 00:38:11,217
- Hey, we got it.
- I think I'm the last person to see her.

453
00:38:13,124 --> 00:38:16,525
I was talking to her right before
she got into the car.

454
00:38:16,560 --> 00:38:18,494
What did you talk to her about?

455
00:38:18,529 --> 00:38:21,896
I needed money.
Somebody stole my basket.

456
00:38:21,932 --> 00:38:24,696
I got no place to carry my stuff.

457
00:38:24,735 --> 00:38:27,295
- Did she give you money?
- No.

458
00:38:27,338 --> 00:38:29,533
What happened after she passed you?

459
00:38:31,742 --> 00:38:33,437
She walked up that way

460
00:38:33,477 --> 00:38:37,174
and then she got into a blue car.

461
00:38:37,214 --> 00:38:40,206
And I didn't see anybody after that

462
00:38:40,251 --> 00:38:42,981
'cause the driver was blocked.

463
00:38:43,020 --> 00:38:44,954
Harper: Do you have any idea
of the make of the car?

464
00:38:44,989 --> 00:38:48,516
Man:
Yeah, it was blue.

465
00:38:48,559 --> 00:38:51,653
Harper:
Do you know what kind of blue car?

466
00:38:51,696 --> 00:38:55,632
Man:
No, my eyes are not so good.

467
00:38:55,666 --> 00:38:58,794
Harper: If I showed you a picture would
you be able to identify the kind of car?

468
00:38:58,836 --> 00:39:01,703
I don't know, maybe.

469
00:39:03,874 --> 00:39:06,900
Man:
It's not right, you know?

470
00:39:06,944 --> 00:39:09,276
She wasn't bothering nobody.

471
00:39:20,624 --> 00:39:23,457
I'm only gonna ask you this once.

472
00:39:23,494 --> 00:39:26,190
Are you fucking okay?

473
00:39:26,230 --> 00:39:28,289
Yeah.

474
00:39:28,332 --> 00:39:30,698
Jesus Christ, are you kidding?

475
00:39:30,735 --> 00:39:34,694
My wrists have carpal tunnel
from typing.

476
00:39:34,739 --> 00:39:37,071
Give me a break.

477
00:39:49,286 --> 00:39:51,151
- Megan.
- Richard.

478
00:39:51,188 --> 00:39:55,056
Hey, I've been thinking about
you ever since I saw...

479
00:39:55,092 --> 00:39:57,185
what's wrong?

480
00:39:57,228 --> 00:40:00,391
- Do you have a few minutes?
- Yeah, come in.

481
00:40:03,367 --> 00:40:05,130
Megan:
I can't stop the restlessness.

482
00:40:05,169 --> 00:40:08,036
I've begun to hallucinate

483
00:40:08,072 --> 00:40:09,903
and hear voices again.

484
00:40:09,940 --> 00:40:13,808
I don't suppose you've talk
to Dr. Parks about this?

485
00:40:13,844 --> 00:40:15,812
No no.
You know what he'd say.

486
00:40:15,846 --> 00:40:19,043
Oh yeah, he'd say,

487
00:40:19,083 --> 00:40:21,074
"Megan, I think you should
be off the case.

488
00:40:21,118 --> 00:40:24,053
I think there's some
misguided martyrdom. "

489
00:40:24,088 --> 00:40:26,386
Yada yada yada.

490
00:40:26,424 --> 00:40:30,656
But still, I don't...

491
00:40:30,694 --> 00:40:33,527
I just don't know
what your suffering...

492
00:40:34,765 --> 00:40:37,928
how that's gonna help
those poor children.

493
00:40:42,406 --> 00:40:45,273
Best thing you can do
is leave Rochester.

494
00:40:45,309 --> 00:40:47,800
I won't stop.

495
00:40:49,079 --> 00:40:52,207
It's in my brain now and it's not
gonna let go until I find him.

496
00:40:52,249 --> 00:40:54,217
You do realize
that's the disease talking?

497
00:40:59,223 --> 00:41:02,215
Okay, I think we're all set.

498
00:41:02,259 --> 00:41:05,251
Yeah.

499
00:41:05,296 --> 00:41:08,231
Okay, now here's the thing:

500
00:41:08,265 --> 00:41:10,733
If you're not gonna listen to reason,

501
00:41:10,768 --> 00:41:13,498
you've got to catch this bastard
as soon as you can

502
00:41:13,537 --> 00:41:15,528
while you're still in one piece.

503
00:41:16,941 --> 00:41:18,704
Okay?

504
00:41:18,742 --> 00:41:20,607
I will.

505
00:41:34,825 --> 00:41:37,055
Carl Tanner, he's a social worker.

506
00:41:37,094 --> 00:41:40,029
- He briefly assisted the Castillos.
- What's this?

507
00:41:40,064 --> 00:41:42,225
A connection.
Carla and Wendy.

508
00:41:42,266 --> 00:41:45,394
We interviewed him two years ago but
his connection to Carla was only tenuous.

509
00:41:45,436 --> 00:41:46,960
So what's he got to do with Wendy?

510
00:41:47,004 --> 00:41:49,029
He's her father's first cousin.

511
00:41:49,073 --> 00:41:50,836
How come no one noticed this?

512
00:41:50,875 --> 00:41:53,241
He changed his name.
It used to be Walsh, now it's Tanner.

513
00:41:53,277 --> 00:41:54,904
- There's another thing.
- What?

514
00:41:54,945 --> 00:41:58,711
In 1982 he chaperoned a school trip
to a canning factory.

515
00:41:58,749 --> 00:42:00,478
A 10-year-old got separated
from the group,

516
00:42:00,518 --> 00:42:02,918
fell from a balcony and died.

517
00:42:02,953 --> 00:42:06,354
- Any evidence of foul play?
- No.

518
00:42:06,390 --> 00:42:08,051
But it's interesting.

519
00:42:15,799 --> 00:42:17,426
Harper:
You go over your notes on this guy?

520
00:42:17,468 --> 00:42:20,028
- Yeah.
- What was he like?

521
00:42:20,070 --> 00:42:22,868
Friendly, eager but not very helpful.

522
00:42:22,907 --> 00:42:24,704
How are you gonna handle him?

523
00:42:24,742 --> 00:42:27,074
You found him.

524
00:42:27,111 --> 00:42:30,410
